<title>04 Setting Up The Ptyxis Terminal</title>

    <p><span>Bluefin (and Bazzite) use the </span><link type="seealso" href="https://gitlab.gnome.org/chergert/ptyxis"><span>Ptyxis terminal</span></link><span>, a container focused terminal designed to make working with containers seamless. Hitting </span><span>Ctrl</span><span>-</span><span>Alt</span><span>-</span><span>t</span><span> will launch a host terminal. We recommend right clicking on the tab and pinning the host, so that you have it handy.</span></p><p><media type="image" src="ptyxis_term.png" mime="image/png" /></p><p><span>And then set a container in the profile settings, </span><code>ubuntu</code><span> or whatever container you want:</span></p><p><media type="image" src="ptyxis_settings.png" mime="image/png" /></p><p><span>Once you get used to a container-native workflow you'll end up naturally in a container.</span></p><p><span>You can pin then both to keep them handy, </span><span>Alt</span><span>-</span><span>0</span><span> and </span><span>Alt</span><span>-</span><span>1</span><span> switch back and forth between the host and the container.:</span></p><p><media type="image" src="ptyxis_containers2.png" mime="image/png" /></p><p><span>All of your distroboxes are available in Ptyxis's tab so you can quickly create new ones as you need them:</span></p><p><media type="image" src="upload://fn3h6el0tYkVKBHrfWqiKArMpEh.png" mime="image/png" /></p>
<section>
 <subtitle><span>Keyboard Shortcuts</span></subtitle><p><span>Ctrl</span><span>Alt</span><span>-</span><span>t</span><span> - opens a host terminal</span></p><p><em style="strong"><span>Note:</span></em><span> (these keyboard shortcuts are currently not functioning):</span></p><p><span>Ctrl</span><span>Alt</span><span>-</span><span>u</span><span> - opens an </span><code>ubuntu</code><span> terminal</span>
 <span>Ctrl</span><span>Alt</span><span>-</span><span>f</span><span> - opens an </span><code>fedora</code><span> terminal</span>
 <span>Ctrl</span><span>Alt</span><span>-</span><span>enter</span><span> - opens a minimal </span><code>bluefin-cli</code><span> terminal with Homebrew. (In progress)</span></p><p><em style="strong"><span>Are you serious?</span></em><span> We don't expect people to use their computer this way (though we need to use it this way to make it, </span><em><span>sigh</span></em><span>). The idea is to show how much flexibility you have when choosing the environment you want to work in. </span><code>ubuntu</code><span> is the intended default and most terminal users will be served just fine with one single container. Here's a good blog post on </span><link type="seealso" href="https://www.ypsidanger.com/declaring-your-own-personal-distroboxes/"><span>generating a declarative distrobox</span></link><span>.</span></p><p><span>Once you get used to a container-native workflow you'll end up naturally in a container and usually  only using the host for system level maintenance like checking for updates manually.</span></p>
</section>

